│ stop({"edit_points": [[3810, 3810, "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp"]],    │
│ "thoughts": "1. **Understanding the Issue**:\nThe vectorizer is aborting due to an         │
│ assertion failure in `LoopVectorizationPlanner::computeBestVF`. The assertion              │
│ `(BestFactor.Width == LegacyVF.Width || planContainsAdditionalSimplifications(...)) && \"  │
│ VPlan cost model and legacy cost model disagreed\"` indicates a discrepancy between the    │
│ vectorization factor (VF) chosen by the new VPlan-based cost model (`BestFactor`) and the  │
│ old legacy cost model (`LegacyVF`). This assertion is a safeguard to ensure the new cost   │
│ model is consistent with the old one during the transition period. In this specific case,  │
│ the VPlan model decides not to vectorize (VF=1), while the legacy model chooses to         │
│ vectorize (VF=8), and the VPlan does not contain any extra simplifications to justify this │
│ difference.\n\n2. **Analyzing `opt`'s Log**:\nThe `opt` command crashes with a SIGABRT     │
│ signal, and the backtrace points directly to the assertion in                              │
│ `LoopVectorizationPlanner::computeBestVF`. The lack of debug output before the crash       │
│ suggests the issue arises during the initial cost analysis and planning phase, before any  │
│ IR transformation occurs. The core of the problem is the disagreement between the two cost │
│ models.\n\n3. **Root Cause Analysis**:\nThrough debugging, I determined that               │
│ `BestFactor.Width` is 1 (scalar) and `LegacyVF.Width` is 8. The disagreement stems from    │
│ how the two cost models evaluate the `zext i1 to i64` operation inside the loop.\n\nThe    │
│ VPlan-based cost model, through `VPCostCalculator::getCost()`, correctly identifies that   │
│ `zext i1 %c to i64` can be widened into a vector of `i1` and then widened to a vector of   │
│ `i64`. It calculates a non-zero, but relatively low, cost for this.\n\nHowever, the legacy │
│ cost model, specifically within `LoopVectorizeCostModel::getScalarizationCost`,            │
│ incorrectly calculates the cost for this `zext` instruction. The relevant code snippet     │
│ is:\n```cpp\n// llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp:3808\nif (isa<ZExtInst>(I) │
│ && I->getOperand(0)->getType()->isIntegerTy(1)) {\n  // zext from i1 can be done using a   │
│ vector select.\n  return TTI.getVectorInstrCost(Instruction::Select, VecTy,                │
│ -1);\n}\n```\nThis logic assumes that a `zext i1 to iN` can be implemented as a `select i1 │
│ %cond, <N x iN> 1, <N x iN> 0`. While this is a valid transformation, the cost is          │
│ calculated by querying `TTI.getVectorInstrCost(Instruction::Select, VecTy, -1)`. For the   │
│ RISC-V target with the V extension, this returns a cost of 0. This zero cost is incorrect; │
│ while the operation is cheap, it is not free.\n\nThis erroneously low (zero) cost in the   │
│ legacy model makes vectorization seem highly profitable, leading it to choose a VF of 8.   │
│ In contrast, the VPlan model's more accurate, non-zero cost leads it to conclude that      │
│ vectorization is not profitable, hence it chooses a VF of 1. This discrepancy triggers the │
│ assertion.\n\nThe fix is to adjust the legacy cost model to provide a more realistic cost  │
│ for this operation. Instead of returning a fixed cost based on a `select`, it should       │
│ return `TTI.getCastInstrCost(Instruction::ZExt, VecTy, I->getOperand(0)->getType())`,      │
│ which will query the target for a more accurate cost of a vector `zext`.\n\n4. **Proposed  │
│ Edit Point(s)**:\nThe issue lies in `LoopVectorizeCostModel::getScalarizationCost` where   │
│ the cost of a `zext` from `i1` is underestimated.\n\n```cpp\n//                            │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp:3808\nif (isa<ZExtInst>(I) &&              │
│ I->getOperand(0)->getType()->isIntegerTy(1)) {\n  // zext from i1 can be done using a      │
│ vector select.\n  return TTI.getVectorInstrCost(Instruction::Select, VecTy,                │
│ -1);\n}\n```\nThis should be changed to:\n```cpp\n//                                       │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp:3808\nif (isa<ZExtInst>(I) &&              │
│ I->getOperand(0)->getType()->isIntegerTy(1)) {\n  // zext from i1 can be done using a      │
│ vector select.\n  return TTI.getCastInstrCost(Instruction::ZExt, VecTy,\n                  │
│ I->getOperand(0)->getType());\n}\n```\n\n5. **Conclusion**:\nBy changing                   │
│ `TTI.getVectorInstrCost(Instruction::Select, ...)` to                                      │
